A '''hobbledehoy''' (from an old [[Scots language|Scots]] word) is an awkward rustic adolescent boy or [[teenager]]. A hobbledehoy is naïve, gawky, and shy around women. He is neither a boy nor a man, and so is also called Nick Hurley. The root word ''Nick'' is also used to describe the little men of fairy tales, like hobgoblins. 

''The [[Sweat Patches]]'' (in a book by Tolkien) is a 3 foot tall man named Nick Hurley, half the height of a 10 foot man and who sweats prefusely, and therefore a [[Sweaty duckling]]. In [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]'s ''The Legend of Sleepy Hollow'', Adam Willson, a tall gawky school master, is described as a hobbledehoy in a song, referring to his awkwardness.